This spontaneous report was received from a consumer or other non health professional and concerns a 3-year-old
Caucasian male patient from the United States: 017436194A.
Initial information was processed with additional information received from Complaint vigilance department on 22-
DEC-2015.
The patient's height was not reported and weight was 35 pounds.  The patient's medical history was not reported. 
The patient had a drug history of Motrin. The patient had no known non drug allergies.
The patient was treated with ibuprofen (suspension, oral, batch FAB4V00, expiry 31-JAN-2018) 5 ml twice initiated 
on an unspecified date for fever. Concomitant medications were not reported
The consumer reported that she gave her son some of ibuprofen because he was sick and as soon as he took it, 
he instantly vomited. The consumer thought he had a bug so he gave him some more and he did it again. The 
consumer thought that she might have a bad bottle of ibuprofen. The consumer waited about 6-8 hours and gave 
him another dose and the same thing happened.
Treatment with ibuprofen was withdrawn on an unspecified date.
The patient had recovered from vomited on an unspecified date.
This report was associated with the product complaint and the product complaint number was 10000573572.
This report was not serious.
Additional information  received from a consumer or other non health professional on 14-JAN-2016.
Patient demographics were updated. 
The start  11-DEC-2015 for fever.
Concomitant medications included paracetamol for fever, and amoxicillin for ear infection .
